<DOC><DOCNO> AP880418-0154 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-88 1528EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Korea     04-18 0325</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Korea,0337</SECOND><HEAD>Students Jog Through Seoul to Protest Against Government, UnitedStates</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   About 20,000 anti-government studentsshouted protests and scattered anti-U.S. leaflets on Monday, theanniversary of a 1960 popular uprising.   National police, meanwhile, were put on top alert afterPresident Roh Tae-woo called for severe punishment of politicalactivists who resort to violence. Roh, worried by clashes betweenpartisans of rival political parties, said his government would not``tolerate violent and seditious acts'' in campaigning for NationalAssembly elections on April 26.   The government had mobilized about 35,000 riot police over theweekend to protect campaign rallies nationwide.   Opposition leader Kim Young-sam accused the governing DemocraticJustice Party of using ``gangsters'' to impede opposition rallies.He said government officials were turning to the autocratic tacticsof former President Chun Doo-hwan.   In the southern city of Suwon on Monday, students hurled teargas grenades and firebombs at a governing party office, but therewere no reports of injury.   The students in Seoul chanted ``Down with dictatorship!'' asthey joined in a 10-mile run from Korea University to acommemorative cemetery and back, turning the annual event into ahuge anti-government demonstration.   The annual run commemorates the April 1960 popular uprising thatprotested election procedures and helped topple autocraticPresident Syngman Rhee.   Riot police remained on alert along the course but did notintervene.   The students' leaflets criticized both the government and theUnited States. Anti-U.S. sentiment has grown this year asWashington pressured South Korea to open its markets.   After Monday's run, about 5,000 students regrouped at KoreaUniversity for a rally supporting labor rights.   They called for joint struggle with striking workers, chargingthe government with suppressing labor unions and their demands fora better life.   The students also shouted ``Yankee go home!'' and called forremoval of U.S. nuclear weapons from South Korea. Many Koreansbelieve the 40,000 U.S. troops stationed in their country keepnuclear weapons.</TEXT></DOC>